%N A395450 Triangle of the Lagrange inversion coefficients for exponential formal power series, indexed by partitions in A334439 order.
%C A395450 The terms T(n, lambda) are the coefficients of the compositional inverse g of f, where g(f(x)) = x, for the exponential formal power series f(x) = Sum_{j>=1} a_j * x^j / j! with a_1 = 1. Here, lambda is a partition index, and the partitions lambda |- n follow the sum-length-revlex ordering defined in A334439. The coefficients are given by T(n, lambda) = (-1)^k * (n + k)! / Product_{v >= 1} m_v! * ((v + 1)!)^(m_v), where k is the number of parts and m_v is the multiplicity of part v. The empty partition is included, with T(0, []) = 1 and T(n, []) = 0 for n >= 1.
%C A395450 With these notations, the Lagrange inversion formula in its exponential form can be stated as
%C A395450   ((n + k)! / k!) * [x^(n + k)] g(x)^k = Sum_{lambda in P(n, k)} T(n, lambda) * Product_{i=1..k} a_(lambda_i + 1) where P(n, k) = {lambda |- n and length(lambda) = k}.
%C A395450 Summing the right-hand side over partition lengths (k = 0 to n) yields
%C A395450 (n + 1)! * [x^(n + 1)] g(x) = Sum_{lambda |- n} T(n, lambda)*Product_{i>=1} a_(lambda_i + 1).
%C A395450 For example, choosing a(j) = 1 for all j gives f(x) = e^x - 1 and g(x) = log(1 + x), yielding the row sum identity Sum_{lambda |- n} T(n, lambda) = (-1)^n * n!.
%C A395450 The coefficients refine the Ward numbers. Let S(n, k) = Sum_{j} T(n, j), where the sum collects the partitions of the same length (adjacent terms with equal sign in the table below), then S(n, k) = (-1)^k*W(n, k), where W(n, k) are the Ward set numbers A269939.
%H A395450 Peter Luschny, <a href="/A395450/b395450.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..9320</a>, rows 0..25.
%H A395450 Ira M. Gessel, <a href="https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.1609.05988">Lagrange inversion</a>, arXiv:1609.05988 [math.CO], Journal of Combinatorial Theory, Series A, vol 144, 212-249 (2016).
%H A395450 Josef Hofbauer, <a href="https://www.mat.univie.ac.at/~slc/">Lagrange-Inversion</a>, Séminaire Lotharingien de Combinatoire, 6, B06a, (1982).
